<seg id="1">Joint report on parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway Preliminary remark Without trans-European motorways, modern, united Europe would only be able to cope with the high volume of traffic between the partner states with significant restrictions and quality losses.</seg>
<seg id="2">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="3">High-quality transport networks are essential for maintaining and increasing living standards in Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">Ensuring fast, safe, reliable and economical passenger and freight transport is an important task for the state.</seg>
<seg id="5">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="6">It requires a great deal of organisational, technical and financial effort.</seg>
<seg id="7">When building and expanding a sustainable European transport infrastructure, difficult compromises often have to be made with European and national policy objectives, such as the preservation of the environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">Precisely because of the necessary environmental protection measures, the construction of the transport infrastructure is complex.</seg>
<seg id="9">When planning and awarding the construction of transport routes, administrations can save considerable financial resources through careful action and decision-making and use them for other useful purposes.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the tasks of state auditing authorities is to identify deficiencies that stand in the way of optimum economy, efficiency and effectiveness in spending on the construction of transport facilities.</seg>
<seg id="11">The audit authorities should not only draw the attention of the administrations to the shortcomings identified, but also make suggestions for improvement for the benefit of the citizens and for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Summary</seg>
<seg id="13">In 2005 and 2006, the two Supreme Audit Institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic, the Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) and the Nejvygl ä u ß t carried out parallel audits of expenditure for the construction of the Prague - Dresden motorway (D 8 motorway in the Czech Republic and A 17 motorway in the Federal Republic of Germany).</seg>
<seg id="14">The two motorways are connected by a border bridge jointly financed by the two states.</seg>
<seg id="15">The cooperation with the NK K ä mpfer enabled the BRH to carry out an in-depth examination of the cost-effectiveness of the use of funds for the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">In the course of the cooperation with the BRH, the NK received data from German bridges and tunnels for its own cost comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany signed a contract for the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the planning progress, the completion date was finally set for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">However, during the tendering process, the Road and Highway Directorate of the Czech Republic (RMD) made mistakes that delayed the procedure and shortened the available construction time.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was therefore concluded later than planned.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor assured the accelerated construction of the bridge by the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">However, the RMD had to accept significant additional costs.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint audit activity, the prices of motorway bridges on the D 8 and A 17 were compared. The benchmark for the price comparison of the bridges was the size of the bridge area.</seg>
<seg id="24">A price analysis using statistical methods identified bridges with high costs per square meter.</seg>
<seg id="25">The analysis showed that the border bridge was the most expensive among the major bridges with lengths of over 100 m.</seg>
<seg id="26">This was also due to the price increase as a result of the delays in awarding contracts.</seg>
<seg id="27">The comparison of the prices of the tunnels showed that the prices of the tunnels in the course of the D 8 are significantly higher than the prices of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">In future audits of the economic viability of transport infrastructure expenditure, both BRH and NK Kr ä fte can rely on a data collection of bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="29">Both courts of auditors recommend standardizing bridge structures and carrying out composite and special steel structures only where prestressed concrete structures are inappropriate.</seg>
<seg id="30">The examination process was characterised by teamwork and an open approach.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel examination, the examiners from both sides exchanged their expertise and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report deals with parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the motorway from Dresden to Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The focus of the audit was on the economy, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness of the use of funds.</seg>
<seg id="35">The parallel tests were carried out by the BRH in Germany and the NK K K ä ufer in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="36">In 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The NK ä r examined the economy, economy and effectiveness of the expenditure for the border section 0807 of the D 8 motorway in the amount of approx. CZK 20 billion gross (approx. €690 million).</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, €64 million will come from EU Structural Funds (ISPA).</seg>
<seg id="39">The BRH had already examined the planning and construction of the A 17 motorway in the years 2003 to 2005, independently of the parallel tests with the NK K K ö rper.</seg>
<seg id="40">Of the approximately €670 million for the construction of all three sections of the A 17, €277 million will be co-financed by the European Fund (ERDF).</seg>
<seg id="41">The Prague-Dresden motorway is part of the Pan-European Corridor IV Dresden - Central and Southeast Europe - Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D8 runs from Prague via Usti nad Labem to the Czech / German border,</seg>
<seg id="43">The A17 from the border to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of the inspection, the border sections of the motorways were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">Both sections were opened to traffic on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">While the motorway is thus completed on the German side to Dresden, the D 8 remains incomplete on the Czech side, as the section 0805 over a length of 16.4 km between Rehlovice and Lovosice is still in the planning phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">The crossing of a landscape protection area in the Bohemian Central Uplands is planned.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to Czech forecasts from 2001, the volume of traffic in 2008 in the border section 0807 of the D 8 motorway will amount to 22,940 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="49">German forecasts estimate the volume of traffic on the A 17 at the Czech border in 2010 at around 25,000 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic signed a contract for the merger of the German A 17 motorway and the Czech D 8 motorway at the common state border by building a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Since both countries are involved in the construction of this bridge, this individual construction project represented an important aspect of the parallel audits of both audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between BRH and NK Kl ä ge</seg>
<seg id="53">From the middle of 2005, the two courts of auditors jointly considered cooperation in the audit of the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both sides had important reasons for this cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany is partly financing the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Planning and construction are the responsibility of the Czech Road Administration.</seg>
<seg id="58">There was no opportunity for the BRH to examine this construction project itself.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The NK did not have any comparative data to assess whether the funds were used sparingly with regard to the total construction costs of the bridges and tunnels on the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The NK ü nstler also had to check the effectiveness of the expenditure by examining the essential technical parameters of the bridges and tunnels, which were to ensure the same quality of use on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">After preparatory negotiations, the presidents of the two courts of auditors concluded an agreement on 4 January 2006 on the coordination of the audits of the Prague-Dresden motorway.</seg>
<seg id="64">In the course of 2006, the auditors of both audit institutions met at intervals of about six to eight weeks.</seg>
<seg id="65">They dealt with current problems and tasks. They developed a uniform methodology for examining the bridge and tunnel prices, exchanged test results for the construction of the border bridge and prepared joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">The ongoing exchange of information was essential to the cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="67">While the BRH focused on the comparison of the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels as well as the award procedures, the NK mainly developed the methodology for the analysis of bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="68">In Germany and the Czech Republic, the legal basis of financial control and thus also the way in which the two courts of auditors complete their audits differ.</seg>
<seg id="69">For this reason, both authorities drew up separate national reports on their audit results.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report takes into account the results of the two parallel audits.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation ends with the signing of a final communication agreement in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of the border bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">In the 2000 treaty, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed to complete the border bridge in 2005 if possible.</seg>
<seg id="74">Later, they mutually postponed the date to the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">The RMD acted as the contractor for the construction project.</seg>
<seg id="76">Germany is contributing 42.13% to the bridge construction.</seg>
<seg id="77">Initially, the RMD provided a prestressed concrete structure for the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, however, RMD agreed with its German partner to build a steel composite structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">They justified this decision with the possible reduction of the number of pillar pairs from seven to five and the associated ecological benefits for the floodplain.</seg>
<seg id="80">In addition, a comparative calculation of the RMD had shown the steel composite structure to be the more cost-effective solution.</seg>
<seg id="81">However, this was based on a calculation error.</seg>
<seg id="82">The calculation was based on a length of the new steel composite structure of only 397 m,</seg>
<seg id="83">In fact, it is 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the award process, the RMD made serious mistakes,</seg>
<seg id="85">By inadequately preparing the award documents and inaccurately describing both evaluation criteria and sub-criteria.</seg>
<seg id="86">These errors led to subjective and ambiguous assessments by the evaluation commission and the director general of the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="87">A losing bidder challenged the outcome of the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">The subsequent investigation by the Czech antitrust office delayed the signing of the construction contract for the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="89">As a result, the summer construction season following the offer review in 2004 was lost and the total construction time available was shortened.</seg>
<seg id="90">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time, resulting in a significant price increase.</seg>
<seg id="91">The measures offered included the double assembly of the superstructures, the change of the pillar shape and the construction of an assembly hall.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the contractor was unable to procure the original steel grade.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new type of steel - whose higher costs of around €4 million were borne by the client alone - made it possible to shorten the construction time provided for corrosion protection and thus the overall construction time.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the offer price of around €18.3 million net, the acceleration measures and other additions will significantly increase the total construction costs of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="95">The shortened construction period alone led to a price increase of about €5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">Excluding price management, costs are currently around €25.9 million net (as of October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of the prices of bridges and tunnels</seg>
<seg id="98">Both courts examined the bridge prices on the D 8 and the A 17 in order to identify the bridges that were characterised by particularly high prices and to compare the bridge prices on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The study was based on mathematical statistical methods.</seg>
<seg id="100">The tunnels on the D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on the German motorways A 71, A 38 and A 4, because there were no comparable tunnels on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="101">A precise definition of the price concept was important in the preparation of this part of the examination.</seg>
<seg id="102">For the comparison of the bridge prices, both courts of auditors agreed on detailed specifications, for example: To use the current price paid for the bridge without VAT.</seg>
<seg id="103">(The VAT rates in the Czech Republic and in Germany are different and may change), not to take into account the costs of special start-up measures, to use the exchange rate of the European Central Bank of 30.12.2005 for currency conversion (29 CZK = 1 €).</seg>
<seg id="104">Bridges of various types (reinforced concrete, prestressed concrete, steel composite and steel) and various sizes are available on both the D 8 and the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="105">To ensure the comparability of the tested bridge structures, the bridges were grouped according to their design.</seg>
<seg id="106">The analyses also took into account the bridge size within these groups.</seg>
<seg id="107">Concrete bridges were by far the most common on both sides of the border (20 bridges on the D 8 and 36 bridges on the A 17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The study focused on this type of bridge, as the size of the sample allowed the application of mathematical statistical methods and improved the reliability of the results.</seg>
<seg id="109">The study showed that the price of the concrete bridges on the D 8 / A 17 depends on the bridge size (length, road surface): The larger the bridge, the lower the square meter price.</seg>
<seg id="110">The correlation between price and size is more pronounced for German bridges than for Czech bridges (see figures below).</seg>
<seg id="111">Two bridges on the A 17 and four bridges on the D 8 were identified at a significantly higher price.</seg>
<seg id="112">These bridges were determined partly by a method for detecting significant deviations within a sample and partly by regression analysis of the correlation between bridge price and size (atypically expensive bridges can be identified based on the distance to the regression curve).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, the atypically high price of these bridges should only serve as an indication of which bridges to focus on.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw definitive conclusions, the causes of the respective high price must be determined in individual cases.</seg>
<seg id="115">This could be due, for example, to inefficient administrative action, but also to environmental protection requirements or other legitimate reasons.</seg>
<seg id="116">Taking into account the larger average length of Czech concrete bridges compared to German ones (see Table 1), the proven negative correlation between the bridge price and the length indicated that Czech concrete bridges are cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">This was also supported by the lower labour costs in the Czech Republic compared to Germany.</seg>
<seg id="118">However, the evaluation of the results showed that the price of the concrete bridges on the D 8 is higher than on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">During joint discussions, two reasons for this situation were identified:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, construction contracts for bridges are mainly awarded separately.</seg>
<seg id="122">This also allows medium-sized companies to participate in the award competition.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic, many bridge constructions are awarded as part of larger contracts for the construction of several kilometres of motorway sections.</seg>
<seg id="124">Orders of this magnitude cannot be managed by medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">In the Czech Republic, the variety of bridge structures built is greater than in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the NK K ä rke noted that the construction of bridges is determined long before construction begins,</seg>
<seg id="128">Already at the submission of the application for planning approval by the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="129">At this point, it selects a specific bridge construction variant from several alternatives. However, cost-effectiveness plays a minor role in this decision.</seg>
<seg id="130">Only a thorough analysis of the construction sectors of both countries would have made it possible to reach a final conclusion with regard to bridge prices in the Czech Republic and Germany. However, this would have gone beyond the scope of this review.</seg>
<seg id="131">The border bridge is the most expensive steel composite bridge on the D8 and A17.</seg>
<seg id="132">The prices for the tunnels on the D8 are about twice as high as in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="133">However, a comparison of the technical parameters between the tunnels on the D 8 and the tunnels in Germany showed no significant difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">The significant price differences may be the result of underdeveloped competition for tunnels in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, the small number of tunnels did not allow generalizing conclusions.</seg>
<seg id="136">Efficiency and effectiveness of the Dresden - Prague motorway</seg>
<seg id="137">The independent Czech Republic was founded in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">In the same year, the government approved the plan for the expansion of the motorway network.</seg>
<seg id="139">The plan was to gradually expand the D 8 from Prague to the state border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">Section 0805 was to be built through the Bohemian Central Uplands before section 0807 near the border.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic is financing the D8 under the programme financing.</seg>
<seg id="142">The programme number 327 220 "Construction of the D 8 Prague motorway - W ä rst ä nstz nad Labem - Czech-German border" defines two objectives:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">As a national goal: To improve the connection between Prague and st i nad Labem;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">As an international destination: The connection between Prague and Berlin as part of the Pan-European Transport Corridor IV BerlinIstanbul.</seg>
<seg id="147">The programme envisaged completion of the construction of the section leading through the Bohemian Central Uplands in June 2008 and the construction of the border section 0807 in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It should be noted that the end of the construction work is not identical to the time of commissioning.</seg>
<seg id="149">The NK stated that the planning approval decision had already been issued for the construction of the section leading through the Bohemian Central Uplands.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental associations have sued against this decision.</seg>
<seg id="151">A final judgment is still pending.</seg>
<seg id="152">Compared to the schedule provided for in the programme documentation, a delay of several years in the completion of section no. 0805 could not be ruled out.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed postponing the completion date of construction phase No. 0805 to 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result, the construction of the border section did not meet the national goal of improving the connection between Prague and Usti nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">The RMD subjected the border-near section no. 0807 of the D 8 and section no. 0805 through the Bohemian Central Uplands to an economic feasibility study between 1999 and 2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">The investment costs for both sections no. 0805 and no. 0807 were approximately €639 million.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Results of the economic feasibility study (EIRR = internal interest rate)</seg>
<seg id="158">Variant Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D8 sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="159">Traffic volume in the northern part of the border section 18 000 cars per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="160">Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D8 sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="161">Traffic volume in the northern part of the border section 22 000 cars per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="162">Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D8 sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="163">Traffic volume in the northern part of the border section 25 000 cars per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="164">The economic feasibility study from 2001 was based on the assumption that the section near the border and the section leading through the Bohemian Central Uplands will be under traffic at the same time.</seg>
<seg id="165">At the time of the test, it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Central Uplands would not be opened on the original date.</seg>
<seg id="166">This reduces the aforementioned EIRR values.</seg>
<seg id="167">As of December 31, 2005, the costs of both sections amounted to €897 million excluding VAT, which is 27.4% higher than the 2001 profitability assessment.</seg>
<seg id="168">In addition, there is a risk that section 0805 will have a different, more complex route, which would affect the profitability of the project.</seg>
<seg id="169">The economic analysis showed that the construction of both motorway sections is economically justified with a daily traffic volume of at least 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010. The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22,940 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="170">However, a study on detour routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Central Uplands assumes a traffic volume of 12,600 to 13,750 vehicles per day in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="171">A higher volume of traffic on the routes, which are to replace the missing section with the Bohemian Central Uplands, is likely to result in congestion and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the original economic feasibility study.</seg>
<seg id="172">The aforementioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the border section of the D8 will not be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">The construction of the section of the D 8 near the border is therefore uneconomical.</seg>
<seg id="174">There were also cost increases in the construction of the A 17, as in the construction of the two above-mentioned sections of the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the macroeconomic assessment for the Federal Transport Infrastructure Plan 1992, the Federal Ministry responsible for transport assumed investment costs of around €320 million.</seg>
<seg id="176">This resulted in a benefit / cost ratio of 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, costs have increased to around €670 million and the benefit / cost ratio has been reduced by more than half.</seg>
<seg id="178">In the years 2003 to 2005, the BRH examined the cost-effectiveness of the planning and construction of the A 17 motorway independently of the parallel tests carried out with the NK K ä mpfer.</seg>
<seg id="179">He noted that the authority responsible for the permit required an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="180">During the audit, the BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the road construction administration of the superfluity of the landscape tunnel.</seg>
<seg id="181">As a result, €10 million in construction costs and €150,000 in annual operating costs were avoided.</seg>
<seg id="182">When examining the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction project was inadequately prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">The following example illustrates this:</seg>
<seg id="184">During the planning phase, the road construction administration did not record the condition of the rock on the surface of the D ö lzschen wall, as it was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">Only when the tunnelling reached the wall did it catch up.</seg>
<seg id="186">It turned out that the rock was more weathered than assumed in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="187">Elaborate measures such as anchorages, injections and rockfall protection nets for around €3.3 million were necessary.</seg>
<seg id="188">The road construction administration not only bore the costs for additional services that were already required, such as securing the D ö lzschener Wand, but also for those that would not have been necessary if the construction preparation had been flawless.</seg>
<seg id="189">These include expenses due to disrupted construction processes (€3.2 million), additional training of the tunnelling team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the construction time extension (€7 million).</seg>
<seg id="190">This additional expenditure of around €10.7 million is not offset by any permanent added value.</seg>
<seg id="191">The BRH took this and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to better exercise its specialist supervision of major road construction measures.</seg>
<seg id="192">In this context, it should insist that the road construction authorities introduce quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Advantages of the cooperation for BRH and NK ä rzte The cooperation met the expectations of both auditors.</seg>
<seg id="194">The BRH received insights into the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="195">Both audit institutions developed a database on bridge and tunnel prices, which will be helpful for future audits.</seg>
<seg id="196">The NK found that the most important structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and roadways of the D 8 are no different from those of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="197">The auditors of both audit institutions involved in the cooperation gained valuable experience that will be useful in future audits.</seg>
</p>
