<p>
<seg id="1">Public procurement of construction services and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report of the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NK K K ä r) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">The awarding of services by contracting authorities is of great importance for both the state and the economy.</seg>
<seg id="5">The state has the task of using public funds as economically and economically as possible and ensuring fair and regulated competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), the awarding of services by contracting authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.</seg>
<seg id="7">In order to ensure largely unrestricted competition across borders, contracting authorities have to comply with EU regulations when awarding contracts above certain value limits (thresholds).</seg>
<seg id="8">To this end, the EU member states must transpose and apply EU procurement law into national law.</seg>
<seg id="9">This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="10">Below the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate public procurement themselves.</seg>
<seg id="11">The awarding of benefits is also an area at risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="12">Due to the inherently high damage potential, contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue favours when awarding their contracts.</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits for both the EU-wide award of construction services and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="14">The focus of the audits was on the application of EU public procurement law, which has been transposed into national regulations, as well as the prevention of corruption in the awarding of construction services in building construction and road construction and transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="15">The allocation below the EU thresholds was also taken into account with regard to corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit results of both courts are summarised in this joint report.</seg>
<seg id="17">The report should also be addressed to international institutions, such as the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="18">Audit areas and audited bodies The evaluations of the Federal Audit Office on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional audits, which it carried out in 2011 / 2012 at the construction administrations, which are responsible for the road and building construction of the federal government in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="19">He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and large construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="20">In addition, the Federal Court of Auditors used results from previous investigations.</seg>
<seg id="21">The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit findings from the years 2008 to 2011. The audits included construction measures in road construction, rail infrastructure construction, hydraulic engineering, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) and other construction areas in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, the public procurement of the federal government is mainly carried out by the construction administrations of the federal states.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, the State Construction Administration is centrally responsible for the procurement of transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="24">In building construction, the awarding of contracts is carried out decentrally by those agencies that use state budget funds.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, freelancers are also involved in some areas of the procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="26">When comparing the evaluations, differences in procurement law and the market structure for construction services in both countries must be taken into account.</seg>
<seg id="27">Development of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is stipulated in laws and regulations.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to the national area are governed by budgetary law and the administrative regulations based on it.</seg>
<seg id="30">In addition, many supplementary individual regulations are stipulated by internal administrative provisions for both EU-wide and national procurement,</seg>
<seg id="31">Such as the so-called "procurement manuals" of the federal government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or formulated in more detail in compliance with procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the Public Procurement Act and other legal provisions, which apply both to the area above and below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="33">The procurement law was significantly amended in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new regulation increased transparency in the use of public funds, enabled greater competition and limited the possibilities for corruption in the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="35">Outlines of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">In both countries, the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiated procedure in particular apply to EU-wide contracts.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold are subject to the national award types (public tender, limited tender, hands-free award), which largely correspond to the EU-wide award types mentioned.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of the primacy of the open procedure (for EU-wide contracts) and the public tender (for national contracts).</seg>
<seg id="39">With the open procedure and the public tender, any interested company can submit an offer.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another key feature of German procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="41">Above all, the division of a total construction project into specialist and partial lots serves this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="42">The individual allocation of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.</seg>
<seg id="43">Both of the aforementioned features of German procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.</seg>
<seg id="44">There are over 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures also apply to construction projects below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="46">An exception is the simplified procedure, where a less stringent procedure may be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.</seg>
<seg id="47">Czech public procurement law contains provisions, in line with EU law, according to which contracts should be concluded if competition is guaranteed and an advantageous price is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="48">The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow contracting authorities to choose between the open and the non-open procedure.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are more than 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, including about 1,900 companies with 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Construction volume of contracting authorities and shares of the types of contracts in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In Germany, the total construction volume in 2011 was 307 billion euros.</seg>
<seg id="52">Of this, 45.5 billion euros were allocated to public construction (15%), which, in addition to federal construction, also includes the construction measures of the federal states and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The federal government's construction volume in building construction and highway construction (excluding rail infrastructure construction and hydraulic engineering) amounted to 8.5 billion euros.</seg>
<seg id="54">The volume of contracts for construction work in construction and highway construction by the federal government in 2011 was distributed as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public tenders, 12.7% non-open procedures and limited tenders and 6.6% negotiated procedures and open contracts.</seg>
<seg id="55">Of these, 33.2% were Europe-wide contracts.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public works projects in the Czech Republic amounted to 4.7 billion euros in 2011, representing about 25% of the total volume of all construction projects in the Czech Republic.</seg>
