<seg id="60">The above-mentioned data show that the parallel audits of both countries focus on a significant part of public procurement, that the prevention of corruption is of great financial importance in all contracts and that the open procedure and the public tender are of outstanding importance in the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of the results of the parallel tests</seg>
<seg id="62">In their countries, the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NK K K ö rper) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel audits on the EU-wide awarding of construction services and on corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="63">In this context, the working groups of both audit institutions compared the corresponding legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the areas of building construction and road construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">In doing so, they essentially stated:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Directives on the award of works by contracting authorities have been transposed into national law in both the Czech Republic and Germany (Nos. 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">In addition to the EU requirements, the procurement regulations of both countries serve to prevent corruption, which differ in their priorities and details (No. 3.2).</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, an essential requirement for the procurement documents is that they must contain all the information required for an appropriate tender.</seg>
