<seg id="115">Basics of EU procurement law and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="116">EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, among other things, the Procurement Coordination Directive and the Remedies Directive, which had to be transposed into national law by the member states.</seg>
<seg id="118">The general award principles of the European Union are, in particular, the competition law, the equal treatment law and the prohibition of discrimination, as well as the transparency law.</seg>
<seg id="119">In order to achieve these goals, the Procurement Coordination Directive contains special regulations for construction work to be awarded throughout the EU.</seg>
<seg id="120">To this end, their estimated order amounts must reach or exceed the current amount of 5,000,000 euros.</seg>
<seg id="121">The rules concern in particular the content of the award documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, compliance with deadlines, inter alia for the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualifications of applicants and the Remedies Directive forms the basis for the legal protection of applicants and bidders.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of possible breaches of public procurement law, affected companies can have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the European Union directives into national law.</seg>
<seg id="124">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">The importance of preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="126">In both countries, there is no legal definition of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="127">Corruption is generally understood as the abuse of a position of trust for private benefit,</seg>
<seg id="128">Which is usually initiated by the beneficiaries of these decisions.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can hamper competition and cause significant economic damage.</seg>
<seg id="130">It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of global economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the European Union, the level of these costs is estimated at 1%.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair practices can call into question trust in the integrity and functioning of the administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of public authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">They have to check the organisational structure and processes of their administrations for areas particularly at risk of corruption in order to take appropriate safeguards against corruption.</seg>
<seg id="135">Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.</seg>
<seg id="136">The award of public works is generally regarded as a particularly corruption-prone area of work.</seg>
<seg id="137">Measures to prevent corruption</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption - in particular bribery and bribery as well as the acceptance and approval of benefits - is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.</seg>
<seg id="139">In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued a guideline and recommendations on corruption prevention in the Federal Administration. In addition to the risk analysis, the following principles must be observed for the awarding area: Priority of public tenders and open procedures, multi-eyes principle and transparency, fundamental separation of planning, awarding and billing, accurate and complete documentation of the awarding procedures.</seg>
<seg id="140">In addition, further anti-corruption provisions have been incorporated into the procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="141">In 2011, the responsible Federal Ministry for Procurement in the area of federal highways introduced an electronically supported control system,</seg>
<seg id="142">With the awarding data such as the estimated costs and the order amounts as well as information on the freelancers involved are collected nationwide and evaluated for abnormalities.</seg>
<seg id="143">In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law.</seg>
<seg id="144">The legal requirements of transparency and equal treatment of bidders as well as the prohibition of all discrimination form the most important basis for preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="145">For public procurement, the Czech government has defined anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.</seg>
<seg id="146">Some of the measures recommended in it have already been incorporated into national procurement law and corresponding administrative provisions UM14.</seg>
<seg id="147">The main provisions of the new legislation are as follows: Lowering the thresholds for smaller contracts, the obligation for the awarding authority to announce contracts in advance, including the reasons for tendering, the prohibition of limiting the number of bidders in closed procedures and thus the abolition of the possibility of bidding by lottery, the introduction of the obligation to publish the contract documents and all annexes, the introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.</seg>
<seg id="148">Examination results on the individual phases of the award procedure</seg>
<seg id="149">Award documents</seg>
<seg id="150">Award documents The award documents must contain all the information that the bidders need for an appropriate tender.</seg>
<seg id="151">In particular, the award documents must enable an accurate calculation.</seg>
<seg id="152">No risks may be transferred to the bidders that cannot be calculated for them.</seg>
<seg id="153">The award documents consist in particular of the service description and the contract terms.</seg>
<seg id="154">They also contain the requirements for proving the qualification (suitability) of the bidders as well as the criteria that are decisive for the selection of the most economical offer.</seg>
<seg id="155">Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="156">The requirements of EU law for the procurement documents are aimed in particular at the technical specifications.</seg>
<seg id="157">These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should limit competition as little as possible.</seg>
<seg id="158">The service description must always be product neutral.</seg>
<seg id="159">Therefore, information about products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only permitted under strict conditions.</seg>
<seg id="160">Avoiding restrictive requirements in the procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="161">In addition, unclear or inaccurate information in the award documents must be avoided, as they open up scope for speculation in the preparation of bids and for manipulation in their evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="162">Regulations of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="163">Same or similar regulations In both countries, the EU legal requirements for the technical specifications are implemented in national law.</seg>
<seg id="164">The services are basically product-neutral without factory specifications.</seg>
<seg id="165">As a rule, the individual services must be subdivided into performance units with the respective quantities in detail in the service descriptions.</seg>
<seg id="166">The prices are to be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. euros per meter or per piece).</seg>
<seg id="167">Only in exceptional cases may services be defined by functional targets.</seg>
<seg id="168">In any case, the service descriptions must be complete and clear.</seg>
<seg id="169">They must contain precise quantities and must not include services for which it is not clear whether they are required.</seg>
<seg id="170">Remuneration according to flat rates or time expenditure should be avoided as much as possible.</seg>
<seg id="171">These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on indefinite specifications in the procurement documents.</seg>
<seg id="172">The service descriptions must enable bidders to prepare their bids safely and without extensive preparatory work.</seg>
<seg id="173">The call for tenders will not be made public until the tender documents have been completed.</seg>
<seg id="174">Differing regulations</seg>
<seg id="175">There is no obligation to tender for construction work in lots in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="176">If it is possible according to the type of service to be commissioned, the public procurement authorities can divide construction services into several lots.</seg>
<seg id="177">In Germany, construction services are generally to be divided into lots, separated by quantity (partial lots) and / or by type or subject area (specialist lots).</seg>
<seg id="178">The aim is to enable medium-sized companies to participate in the competition, expand the number of possible providers and make price agreements more difficult.</seg>
<seg id="179">This type of award is generally considered the most economical.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, evaluation criteria must be stated in the award documents for both EU-wide and national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="181">This should allow applicants to fully and conclusively identify the criteria according to which their offers should be evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="182">In Germany, the indication of evaluation criteria in EU-wide announcements, but at the latest in the award documents, is only required for EU-wide award procedures.</seg>
<seg id="183">In the case of national award procedures, the evaluation criteria are only to be recorded in an internal administrative award note.</seg>
<seg id="184">In Germany, award documents drawn up by commissioned freelancers may not contain any references to these offices or involved planners or surveyors in the building construction and some road construction administrations.</seg>
<seg id="185">This is to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages without the knowledge of the client through contact with these freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="186">This is also the reason why freelancers are not allowed to send procurement documents or interpret planning documents for inspection.</seg>
