<seg id="188">There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="189">Additional or modified services, which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements), are almost always incurred for large construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="190">In both countries, the legal provisions allow the awarding of supplements to the already commissioned company to a certain extent, without the need for a public procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="191">According to EU regulations and German regulations, the remuneration of supplementary services must not exceed half of the main order.</seg>
<seg id="192">In addition, the additional services must not be separated from the main order without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.</seg>
<seg id="193">In the Czech Republic, there is a narrower limit of 20% for awarding contracts without public notice.</seg>
<seg id="194">However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already underway.</seg>
<seg id="195">If supplementary services are also transferred to the already commissioned company, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is not possible according to the regulations in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="196">In determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basis for determining the price of the order already placed must be assumed.</seg>
<seg id="197">In addition to supplementary services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.</seg>
