<seg id="588">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="589">The regulations of both countries for the opening of the offers agree in significant parts. They take into account both the multi-eyes principle and the principle of transparency. This can significantly limit the risks of corruption and manipulation when opening the offers.</seg>
<seg id="590">The requirements in Germany are more comprehensive than those in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="591">In particular, the requirements for the exact documentation of the procedure as well as for the labelling, safe storage and secrecy of the offers significantly limit manipulation possibilities such as subsequent changes to the offers.</seg>
<seg id="592">In addition, the persons responsible for opening the offers may not perform any other tasks in connection with the service to be awarded.</seg>
<seg id="593">The overall few complaints prove the high acceptance of the requirements for the opening of the offer.</seg>
<seg id="594">Examination and evaluation of offers</seg>
<seg id="595">Examination and evaluation of the offers The client must examine and evaluate the offers available at the opening date.</seg>
<seg id="596">It must determine the bid for the award of the contract that best meets the requirements according to the specified award criteria.</seg>
<seg id="597">Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="598">The EU guidelines provide for a multi-stage procedure:</seg>
<seg id="599">First, the suitability of the bidders must be determined.</seg>
<seg id="600">Bidders must be economically and financially efficient and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.</seg>
<seg id="601">Companies that are legally convicted of bribery or fraud, for example, are generally excluded from participation in the award process.</seg>
<seg id="602">The bids of the not excluded bidders must be checked mathematically, technically and economically and evaluated on the basis of the previously announced award criteria.</seg>
<seg id="603">The client has to determine the most economically advantageous offer. Offers with unusually low prices have to be examined by the client in particular.</seg>
<seg id="604">The review and evaluation of tenders is a particularly susceptible phase of the award process.</seg>
<seg id="605">For example, bidders can be unjustifiably excluded or bids that do not meet the requirements can be left in competition.</seg>
<seg id="606">By favouring or disadvantaging bidders, the valuation result can be adversely affected and thus the determination of the economically most advantageous offer can be prevented.</seg>
<seg id="607">The contracting authority must therefore take special precautions to ensure that the persons responsible for the audit and evaluation meet the requirements for integrity and expertise.</seg>
<seg id="608">It must also ensure the transparency and traceability of the procedure and the decisions taken.</seg>
<seg id="609">Regulations of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="610">Same or similar regulations</seg>
<seg id="611">In accordance with EU requirements, offers in both countries must be examined and evaluated in multi-stage procedures.</seg>
<seg id="612">The requirements for the companies' proof of suitability to be submitted as well as the award criteria to be taken into account in the evaluation and their weighting are specified in the notices or in the award documents and cannot be changed during the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="613">After checking the suitability of bids, the eligibility criteria may no longer be used in the evaluation of bids.</seg>
<seg id="614">The evaluation must be limited to the award criteria.</seg>
<seg id="615">The submitted bids must first be formally checked immediately to see whether they are complete and whether they contain, for example, abnormalities that could indicate possible manipulation intentions.</seg>
<seg id="616">If bidders are excluded from further examination and evaluation of their offers, they must be informed immediately.</seg>
<seg id="617">If the evaluation of the bids results in an unreasonably low price, the bidder must be given the opportunity to comment before a possible exclusion of his offer.</seg>
<seg id="618">The decisions made during the review and evaluation of the offers must be documented in a comprehensible manner.</seg>
<seg id="619">Differing regulations</seg>
<seg id="620">In Germany, the offers to be kept secret may only be made available to the persons directly responsible for processing them.</seg>
<seg id="621">Only the contracting authority may carry out the review of the offers and the mathematical examination of the offers.</seg>
<seg id="622">It must only appoint staff who are not involved in the award decision or the implementation of the measure.</seg>
<seg id="623">The performance of further examination and evaluation tasks is not regulated in detail.</seg>
<seg id="624">If freelancers are entrusted with the examination and evaluation, they must treat the offers confidentially.</seg>
<seg id="625">They may only make suggestions for the decisions to be taken by the contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="626">In the Czech Republic, award committees must be set up to examine and evaluate bids.</seg>
<seg id="627">The committees prepare evaluation reports with award proposals.</seg>
<seg id="628">Ultimately, as in Germany, only the contracting authorities have to decide on the contracts.</seg>
<seg id="629">If evidence or declarations required for the submission of bids are only incomplete in Germany, the contracting authority must give the bidders the opportunity to submit the missing documents within six days.</seg>
<seg id="630">Only if the documents are still not available after the deadline, the offer is excluded from the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="631">In the Czech Republic, it is at the discretion of the awarding authority whether it gives bidders the opportunity to complete missing evidence or declarations.</seg>
<seg id="632">If a bidder fails to do so, he must be excluded.</seg>
<seg id="633">In Germany, in addition to the total price, the standard prices (prices for partial services) of the offers must also be investigated.</seg>
<seg id="634">If, due to the price structure of the offer, there are indications of prices being set too low or too high for partial services, the bidder must be asked to remove these ambiguities.</seg>
<seg id="635">If he does not succeed and the contracting authority can provide proof of a mixed calculation of prices, this offer must be excluded.</seg>
<seg id="636">This is to prevent bidders from speculating on significant volume changes in partial services when calculating their offer, which can lead to significant cost increases in the construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="637">In the Czech Republic, the total price is assessed, but not the adequacy of the prices for partial services.</seg>
<seg id="638">A mixed calculation cannot justify the exclusion of an offer.</seg>
<seg id="639">Bids with unreasonably high or low prices may not be awarded in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="640">If one or more bids fall short of the correct price determination of the client or the bid totals of the other bidders by 10% or more, the bidders must prove the correct calculation of their bids.</seg>
<seg id="641">If this is not possible, the contracting authority can exclude the relevant offers.</seg>
<seg id="642">In the Czech Republic, the call for tenders can be cancelled after an economic assessment if only bids with unjustifiable low prices are available.</seg>
<seg id="643">In contrast to German procurement law, the knockdown cannot be refused for offers with prices significantly higher than the client's calculation for this reason.</seg>
<seg id="644">If there is a suspicion of restrictive behaviour in Germany, the contracting authority must immediately report to its specialist supervisory authority.</seg>
<seg id="645">It has to decide which measures should be taken and whether the antitrust authority or the public prosecutor's office should be informed.</seg>
<seg id="646">The supervising level must also agree, for example, for construction work over 50,000 euros, if the contract is to be awarded by hand, if a contract is not to be awarded on the offer with the lowest price or if the tender is to be cancelled.</seg>
<seg id="647">There are no such regulations in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="648">Essential test results</seg>
<seg id="649">BRH</seg>
<seg id="650">Suitability and evaluation criteria</seg>
<seg id="651">The vast majority of the procurement procedures audited complied with the listed requirements.</seg>
<seg id="652">For some companies proposed by freelancers, the contracting authorities did not check the suitability of the companies themselves.</seg>
<seg id="653">A grant recipient commissioned companies without the required proof of suitability being available in full.</seg>
<seg id="654">In some cases, it was not clear whether the awarding authority had taken into account all the announced award criteria in its selection decision or whether it had based its award decision solely on the criterion of "price".</seg>
<seg id="655">Selection of the persons involved and confidentiality of offers</seg>
<seg id="656">Some contracting authorities used unauthorised persons to check the offers.</seg>
