<seg id="695">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="696">The regulations for the examination and evaluation of offers in both countries comply with the requirements of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="697">However, the details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved differ from each other.</seg>
<seg id="698">In Germany, the procedure is more tightly regulated than in the Czech Republic by detailed requirements, especially for the implementation of the multi-eyes principle and for the protection of offers.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the specifications on the basis of which the adequacy of the prices offered must be checked.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, it had to be established in some of the audited procurement procedures that significant procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of the tenders were not or only insufficiently documented.</seg>
<seg id="701">However, without traceability and transparency of the audit and evaluation decisions, possible manipulative interventions are favoured.</seg>
<seg id="702">A particularly serious defect was the handing over of all offers to third parties without the contracting authority having sufficiently reviewed and documented the offers beforehand, thus protecting them from possible manipulation in the further proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="703">If contracting authorities have tasks carried out by third parties in the examination and evaluation of the offers, sufficient precautions and an increased control effort are required to counter the increased risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="704">When assessing the adequacy of prices, the audited services in Germany did not always make full use of the prescribed instruments and did not adequately examine the price structure of the offers.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, there were complaints mainly about the aptitude test and the application of the evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="706">Conclusion of the award process</seg>
<seg id="707">After examining and evaluating the bids, the award procedure is completed by awarding the contract or by cancelling the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="708">Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="709">In EU-wide procurement procedures, all bidders must be informed in advance of the planned award decision.</seg>
<seg id="710">The companies have the opportunity to check the intended award in the case of information by electronic means or by fax within 10 days or in the case of other means of communication within 15 days and, if necessary, to initiate a review procedure.</seg>
<seg id="711">A contract may not be concluded before the end of this information period.</seg>
