<seg id="755">Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption The documentation of procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="756">A carefully and promptly prepared documentation enables the traceability of the award decisions.</seg>
<seg id="757">In particular, it also serves the effective legal protection of bidders in the event of contracts being awarded above the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential part of avoiding corruption, as the obligation to justify award decisions in detail significantly restricts scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">The notice of a contract awarded in an EU-wide procurement procedure must be sent to the EU Publications Office within 48 days.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU, also implementing the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authorities also have to collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the EU Commission via the relevant national ministries.</seg>
