<seg id="801">Construction administrations should further improve the transparency of their procurement procedures and contracts and fully comply with their reporting and reporting obligations.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">The parallel audits conducted by the NK and the BRH focused on two main areas that are essential in the Czech Republic and Germany for the awarding of works by contracting authorities: The application of EU procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">The requirements of EU law enable cross-border competition to create a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Anti-corruption measures are not only intended to prevent or at least reduce corruption, but also to avert economic damage and a possible loss of trust in the integrity of the state.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two courts of auditors on the application of procurement law in both countries and the comparison of these regulations provide information on similarities and differences, which can be helpful for both countries in the further development of their procurement law and its application.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement rules</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed the EU requirements for awarding construction contracts into national law.</seg>
<seg id="809">This gives the Czech Republic and Germany an important common basis for awarding construction contracts and taking into account the essential requirements of competition, equal treatment of the companies involved and the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">The construction administrations of both countries have partially supported these bids very extensively with further administrative regulations.</seg>
<seg id="811">To a large extent, the Czech Republic has also transferred the requirements for construction services to be awarded throughout the EU to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, investigations by the courts of auditors have shown that the construction authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.</seg>
<seg id="813">The construction administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to eliminate the objections identified when implementing the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">Above all, the audits in the Czech Republic have identified risks that affect the profitability of the contracts.</seg>
<seg id="815">Incomplete service descriptions necessitated additional services, which were often awarded in violation of legal regulations. In addition, the cost assessments were usually inadequately prepared. Excessive qualification requirements also reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, especially in transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">The investigations did not aim to uncover cases of corruption,</seg>
<seg id="818">This is also because the courts of auditors do not have the appropriate instruments.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, the courts of auditors can check to what extent the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation when awarding construction contracts and how these requirements are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">The two countries have set different priorities for preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="821">Above all, the German regulations provide for largely unrestricted competition as well as transparency and controls as key elements in preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">The Czech regulations are primarily aimed at increasing the transparency of procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply, which must be applied by the entire federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of construction services and are geared to their specific requirements.</seg>
<seg id="826">In some cases, the relevant regulations specify very precisely how the bids for corruption prevention are to be taken into account in the course of the procurement procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.</seg>
<seg id="827">In the opinion of the BRH, in particular the primacy of the principle of the open procedure or the public tender is a suitable instrument to significantly reduce the risk of corruption when awarding construction services. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative interference.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analyses and adequate controls (especially the multi-eyes principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures and various organisational measures are also effective precautions to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The BRH therefore sees no need for fundamental changes to the corresponding requirements of the administrations when awarding construction services.</seg>
<seg id="830">The rules for preventing corruption are largely taken into account in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">The shortcomings identified in some areas have highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some benchmarks.</seg>
<seg id="832">The construction authorities should further train their employees on the requirements for corruption prevention and make them even more aware of this problem.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the complaints related to tasks that the construction authorities had delegated to freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="834">Without controls and adequate safeguards, however, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.</seg>
<seg id="835">Tampering and corruption-prone tasks should therefore only be delegated to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient level of protection against unauthorised interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">NK Catching up</seg>
<seg id="837">At government level, the Czech Republic adopted a strategy against corruption, in which public procurement is the most important component.</seg>
<seg id="838">The Procurement Act and the associated implementing provisions have been substantially amended.</seg>
<seg id="839">The audits of the NK Kr ä ger took place during the implementation of this strategy.</seg>
<seg id="840">The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions should be effective improvement measures, since the contracting authorities must justify the profitability of the contracts, the calculation of the expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the nature of the evaluations, and all these aspects must be properly documented and published.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">In principle, the NK K ä mpfe and the BRH assess the implementation of the EU requirements positively.</seg>
<seg id="843">The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU requirements of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for awarding construction contracts within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="844">The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting cross-border competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">In view of the enormous material and non-material damage potential caused by manipulation and corruption in the awarding of construction services, both courts of auditors see the construction administrations in their countries as required to continue their measures against corruption and manipulation and, if necessary, to improve them.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to take appropriate countermeasures.</seg>
<seg id="847">The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the share of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures offer a wider scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="848">A greater division of construction services into lots can also have a positive impact on supply prices, provided that this leads to greater competition with a higher number of bidders.</seg>
<seg id="849">Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for efficient public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by specialised construction administrations. In the Czech Republic, on the other hand, with the exception of transport construction projects, these tasks are carried out by the departments themselves or by contractors commissioned by them.</seg>
<seg id="851">Even after the completion of their joint project, the courts of auditors of both countries are keen to further develop the findings that are important to them and, if necessary, to bring them to the attention of their country's parliament and government.</seg>
<seg id="852">Both courts of auditors are also convinced that the principles of public procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at international level to the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), because the principles and findings presented are of general importance in order to effectively combat corruption and to ensure the economic award of works in a well-functioning and fair competition.</seg>
