<seg id="11">In 2006, the courts of auditors of both countries audited the VAT for the first time in parallel.</seg>
<seg id="12">The audit report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">Since VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the courts of auditors is required, which will allow a comprehensive assessment of whether the measures taken are suitable for effectively combating VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two courts decided to continue their cooperation and conducted a second parallel audit. VAT administration in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany Report on the audit</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Examination number: (CZ) 09 / 11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Administration of the VAT (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as NKK), audit</seg>
<seg id="18">Examination goal:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The VAT administration and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as Germany) should be examined. In addition, the procedures used by the tax authorities for intergovernmental administrative assistance should be examined.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit was intended to evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="21">In addition, further examination fields linked to the VAT should be processed.</seg>
<seg id="22">The findings should be compared in order to determine whether the tax procedures can be optimised.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audit period was from 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period before the audit period until the completion of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination</seg>
<seg id="25">The courts of auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed on an audit for the administration of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="26">In the previous parallel investigation, they had uncovered suspected cases of intra-Community transactions,</seg>
<seg id="27">Which made a re-examination seem appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="28">Based on the audit findings, the two courts of auditors made recommendations on the administration of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="29">The aim of the audit was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented and to investigate the suspected cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit also dealt with other issues, including selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of VAT receivables and the VAT audit of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="31">The Court of Auditors found:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous review</seg>
<seg id="33">Recommendation 1: The rules for the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In the first audit, the courts of auditors compared the registration procedures for VAT in the two states and found differences that caused problems.</seg>
<seg id="35">The courts therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxpayers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This has also been taken up at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798 / 2003 provides for the extension of the current databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of VAT payers.</seg>
<seg id="38">The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their eventual cancellation.</seg>
<seg id="39">The Courts of Auditors expected Member States to agree on appropriate rules, in line with their decision in principle, to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the VAT system as early as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">The Member States reached political agreement in ECOFIN on the latest version of the draft.</seg>
<seg id="41">The aforementioned common rules are no longer included, and the two courts of auditors regret that.</seg>
<seg id="42">They still consider such regulations to be important in order to prevent VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary reports As a result of the first audit, the Court of Auditors recommended to the Member States that the summary reports (CM) should be submitted monthly in future.</seg>
<seg id="44">The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be reviewed more promptly.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008 / 117 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC on the common system of value added tax (VAT) for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has shortened the deadline for submitting the ZM to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the VAT Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the implementation did not come into force until July 1, 2010. It has thus not transposed the obligation to submit the ZM monthly into national law on time.</seg>
<seg id="48">Recommendation 3: Data comparison of VAT pre-registrations and ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to examine the merging of the procedures for VAT pre-registrations and ZM The German tax administration has taken up the recommendation made by the Federal Court of Auditors and set up a working group to develop possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="49">The work has not yet been completed.</seg>
<seg id="50">The Federal Audit Office will monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">Recommendation 4: Exchange on successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level During the first audit, the two courts agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The Court found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems, which have both strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">The NKU audited the information exchange system within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Federal Court of Auditors focused on Germany's participation in the "Platform for Risk Management".</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Audit of selected intra-Community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">During the first audit, the courts of auditors jointly examined transactions in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been carried out or which had been explained differently by the taxpayers of the two states in the VAT declarations (or VAT declarations) or ZM.</seg>
<seg id="58">The Court of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for the audit.</seg>
<seg id="59">The audits by the tax offices (F Ä) of both states had not yet been completed at the conclusion of the first parallel audit.</seg>
<seg id="60">The audit has shown that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed, and the respective tax administrations have taken appropriate measures to this end (including subsequent VAT fixing or the prevention of VAT refunds).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-Community transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">The audit also included highly risky intra-Community transactions between EU taxpayers covered by the EUROCANET system.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is used to identify taxpayers at risk.</seg>
