<seg id="617">5. Conclusions</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation between the two audit institutions has proved its worth.</seg>
<seg id="619">In this way, necessary insights into the systems used in both countries could be gained: This concerns in particular: Intra-community transactions, risk management at the VAT in particular with regard to the selection of risky transactions, debt recovery of VAT receivables and VAT audit of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="620">The audit revealed differences in VAT fraud detection strategies and in the systems described above.</seg>
<seg id="621">These findings can be used to improve existing procedures.</seg>
<seg id="622">They can also be used to initiate a discussion with the interested parties as to which audit approaches and strategies can be used to combat fraud, for example in the relationship within and between the Member States and the EU Commission.</seg>
<seg id="623">The experience and insights gained should encourage us to continue to jointly examine the administration of VAT in the future.</seg>
